# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scaleway
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:scaleway/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Storage in such services is organised as blocks.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] This emulates the type of behaviour seen in traditional disks or tape storage through storage virtualization.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Blocks are identified by an arbitrary and assigned identifier by which they may be stored and retrieved, but this has no obvious meaning in terms of files or documents.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] A file system must be applied on top of the block-level storage to map 'files' onto a sequence of blocks.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Amazon EBS (elastic block store) is an example of a cloud block store.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Cloud block-level storage will usually offer facilities such as replication for reliability, or backup services.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Block-level storage is in contrast to an object store or 'bucket store', such as Amazon S3 (simple storage service), or to a database.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] These operate at a higher level of abstraction and are able to work with entities such as files, documents, images, videos or database records.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Instance stores are another form of cloud-hosted block-level storage.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] These are provided as *part of* an 'instance', such as an Amazon EC2 (elastic compute cloud) service.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] As EC2 instances are primarily provided as compute resources, rather than storage resources, their storage is less robust.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Their contents will be lost if the cloud instance is stopped.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] As these stores are part of the instance's virtual server they offer higher performance and bandwidth to the instance.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] They are best used for temporary storage such as caching or temporary files, with persistent storage held on a different type of server.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] At one time, block-level storage was provided by storage area networks (SAN), and network-attached storage (NAS) provided file-level storage.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] With the shift from on-premises hosting to cloud services, this distinction has shifted.
[src:scaleway/block-level-storage] Even block-storage is now seen as distinct servers (thus NAS), rather than the previous array of bare disks.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] The company was founded by Xavier Niel in 1990.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] Iliad is the 5th largest European telecommunications group with 50 million subscribers through its subsidiaries in France, Italy, and Poland.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] Free Mobile, a subsidiary of Iliad, was launched in 2012.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] As of December 2013, it was France's fourth largest mobile operator, having gained a 12% share of the market.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] On August 1, 2014, Iliad publicly announced a bid to acquire a 56% stake in the United States wireless carrier T-Mobile for US$16 billion.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] The bid came amidst reports that competing carrier Sprint Corporation, owned by Japanese firm Softbank, was planning its own US$24 billion merger.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] As of the end of 2012, the company was active in over 35 countries.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] In 2019, Iliad made 5.33 billion revenue.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] Iliad Italia, an Italian subsidiary of Iliad, was launched in Milan, Lombardy on May 29, 2018.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] In May 2019, Iliad and Salt sold a majority of their telecommunications towers in France, Italy, and Switzerland to Cellnex Telecom for €2.7 billion — €2 billion for Iliad (covering 70% of its towers) and €700 million for Salt (90% of its towers).
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] The deal included approximately 5,700 towers in France and 2,200 in Italy.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] In September 2020, Iliad acquired Play, the largest mobile operator in Poland, for US$4.2 billion.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] In July 2021, Xavier Niel, founder of Iliad, announced the acquisition of the remaining 29% of the company he did not already own, in a US$3.7 billion deal.
[src:scaleway/iliad-company] In September 2021, Iliad acquired UPC Poland, a subsidiary of Liberty Global, for €1.5 billion.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:scaleway/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] As of 2015, Scaleway is the second largest hosting company in France.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In August 2002, the domain name registrar BookMyName was bought by Iliad from its competitor LDCom.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In May 2006, rental of dedicated servers through the Dedibox brand was launched.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In December 2008, Iliad bought Alice ADSL: They also took over construction and operation of Datacenters, launched in 1999 by ISDnet, bought by Cable & Wireless in January 2000 acquired by Tiscali France in June 2003 and finally renamed as Iliad Datacenter.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In April 2010, Online merges with Dedibox, another subsidiary of Iliad, bringing together different hosting activities under a single brand.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In 2012, the company has opened its third datacenter of 11800 m² in Vitry-sur-Seine after 11 months of construction works.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] The site received the first Tier-III certification in France by Uptime Institute in January 2014.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] Since 2012, the company publishes in real time the PUE of its datacenters on pue.online.net, in an effort of transparency.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In 2013, Online launched labs.online.net in preview.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] An infrastructure as a service offer, based on dedicated hardware and without virtualization, based on ARM CPUs.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] The hardware is made in a factory near Laval in France.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In April 2015 the service left its beta status and has been renamed as Scaleway.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] As the popularity of the platform grows, Online added servers with x86_64 based CPUs in March 2016.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In early 2015, the company announced to have exceeded 400 Gb/s of immediate Internet traffic.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] Entrepreneur Yann Lechelle joined as CEO in early 2020, but left in December 2022.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] In November 2023, Iliad launched Kyutai in France, the first European independent and non-profit artificial intelligence research laboratory, a laboratory that adopts an open-source and open-science approach for 300 million Euro.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] According to Euractiv, the European Commission has been in talks for several weeks about European cloud providers as alternatives to Microsoft, including Scaleway.
[src:scaleway/scaleway] Scaleway owns and operates several data centers located in Île-de-France.
